b"Ivy\xe2\x80\x99s husband has a history of #stroke and was diagnosed with #pneumonia after catching #flu. Since then, Ivy's husband has been getting vaccinated against #influenza each year per his doctor\xe2\x80\x99s advice. She is still worried about her husband\xe2\x80\x99s health so she takes care of herself to take care of her loved one. Hear from Ivy and others in our story on"

b'Working full-time and leading an active lifestyle, independence has always been important to Larry. But when he caught flu, he ended up being bed-bound for several weeks and relying on others to do daily tasks. He\xe2\x80\x99s never regained full strength. The flu not only changed his health, but his entire way of life. \n\nOlder adults are more at risk of serious complications from the flu. Hear from Larry and others in our story on sanofi.com'
b'Today we announced our Q3 2020 financial results. Full details on Sanofi.com'

b'The purpose of Sanofi\xe2\x80\x99s Consumer Healthcare is to serve healthier, fuller lives every day across the globe. 

To celebrate this, each year employees come together for Purpose Day, partnering with local NGOs to conduct volunteer activities in their communities. This year over 4,000 employees in 40 countries volunteered in online and offline events.

Here we see a glimpse of that action, with pictures from Turkey, Cambodia, Singapore and France. Thank you to all who participated!

#EmpoweringLife #Sanofi #volunteering #CorporateResponsibility'

b'Hearing from people like Juan Guillermo reminds us of the suffering polio causes and the importance of vaccination. \n\nListen to his story to find out more about what it\xe2\x80\x99s like living with the effects of polio \xe2\x80\x93 click the link in our bio to watch the whole video. #WorldPolioDay #EndPolioNow'

b'Local heroes are working to mitigate the impact #COVID19 has had on vaccination programs in Pakistan. \n\nUntil there are no children infected with polio, the virus remains a risk to all. Click the link in our bio to watch the whole video and learn more. #WorldPolioDay #EndPolioNow'

b'Ahead of #WorldPolioDay we\xe2\x80\x99re celebrating how far we\xe2\x80\x99ve come in the fight against polio.

Yet despite the amazing efforts of global health partners around the world, the fight to #EndPolioNow continues.

Click the link in our bio to find out more.'

b'If you are 65+ years old and/or have existing health conditions, you are more vulnerable to experiencing serious complications from #flu. You can help protect yourself by getting vaccinated. Learn more on Sanofi.com'

b'The risk of having a #heartattack is up to 10x greater within the first seven days after having #flu. Help protect yourself against flu and its serious complications by getting vaccinated. Learn more on Sanofi.com'

b'#Flu can cause serious health complications, even a #heartattack or a stroke, especially in those aged 65+ or people with existing health conditions. By getting vaccinated, you can help protect yourself against flu. \nLearn more on Sanofi.com'

b'How do you keep an escape artist like #cancer contained? Meet Iris Valtingojer, Group Leader of Molecular Oncology Research, who tells us about her team\xe2\x80\x99s work investigating treatment resistance in cancer and shares the inspiration that led her to become a scientist. \n#Oncology #CancerResearch #SanofiScience'

b'Climate change is one of the greatest challenges of our age, and impacts the health of populations around the world. We strive to mitigate the effects of our activities on the environment. Aiming to source 100% #renewable electricity across our operations is just one of the ways we are working to reduce our carbon footprint. Find out more on sanofi.com. \n#ClimateWeekNYC'

b'This World Atopic Dermatitis Day, join us and @Regeneron as we search for new ways to help the #AtopicDermatitis (AD) community navigate the uncertainty of their disease. Submit your idea for the 2020 \xe2\x80\x98Agents of Change\xe2\x80\x99 AD Challenge today at https://bit.ly/2Y3TFsG.'

b'Sanofi has battled alongside the @WHO for almost two decades to wipe out #SleepingSickness and has witnessed a decrease, but the battlefield is vast: 57 million people remain at risk in 36 countries.

We\xe2\x80\x99re proud to announce one step forward with our partnership with @drugsforneglecteddiseases to co-develop an innovative treatment that Sanofi will donate for free, once approved.

As most people affected by sleeping sickness live in remote rural areas, this single-dose oral treatment could solve, once approved, many of the problems associated with the \xe2\x80\x9clast mile\xe2\x80\x9d of getting a treatment to patients. 

Learn more about Sanofi\xe2\x80\x99s commitment on sanofi.com

#InfectiousDisease #trypanosomiasis #NeglectedDiseases #beatNTDs'

b'Today we announce the start of the Phase 1/2 clinical trial for our #COVID19 vaccine candidate developed in collaboration with @GSK, following encouraging pre-clinical study results. Read more on sanofi.com\n#FightCOVID19 #SanofiActs'

b'Today is #WorldMosquitoDay. Back in 1897, Dr. Ronald Ross discovered that #malaria was transmitted by a #mosquito. But did you know there are thousands of species of mosquito, which carry different diseases?'

b'Last week we announced #COVID19 vaccine supply agreements with the UK and US governments.
In partnership with @gsk, we are working to develop a safe and effective vaccine based on the recombinant protein technology used by Sanofi to produce an influenza vaccine, and GSK\xe2\x80\x99s established pandemic adjuvant technology.
Our ambition? Making this vaccine available to everyone. Learn more on sanofi.com.

#vaccines #coronavirusoutbreak #coronaviruspandemic #SanofiActs'

b'#PrideMonth might be over, but Sanofi\xe2\x80\x99s support of the LGBTIQ community continues year round:\nToday, hear from Kornrawee Putthasook, Marketing Coordinator in Thailand, on the obstacles she faced while job hunting: "During the five years I spent looking for a job, it was difficult to find a company that was open and would accept me as a #transgender woman. One time I had the chance to have an interview but then it was cancelled, because I\xe2\x80\x99m transgender. And then I met Sanofi, and I felt accepted for who I am."'

b'#Pride2020\nBefore coming out, Emmanuel Desproges, IT leader Australia, New Zealand and South Korea, wore a mask to work every day: "It was exhausting. I wasn\xe2\x80\x99t pretending to be straight, just trying to be as invisible as possible." Check Sanofi.com to watch all our employees\' stories.'
b'To celebrate #PrideMonth, our employees around the world share their stories. Today, meet Karen Herrera, HSE Manager for Sanofi Mexico.\n#OneFaceOneStory'

b'Developing and manufacturing #vaccines is a complex journey that normally takes considerable time to produce, test, package and deliver high quality, safe and effective vaccines that protect public health.

#Sanofi SVP Vaccines Global R&D John Shiver discusses the mechanics of developing a vaccine in response to a pandemic such as #COVID19
"Because the industry is pursuing new methods to combat COVID-19, widespread, accelerated success will be challenging but can be accomplished when science, manufacturing and regulators work with urgency toward a common purpose."
#SanofiActs'
